ionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: occupational name, status name from Norman French  <i>bacaler</i> ‘a young knight, a novice in arms’. The [k] is a characteristically Norman form where Central French has [tʃ];  see  Batchelor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Backner","meanings":["1  English: occupational name from Middle English * <i>baconer</i>, * <i>baconour</i> ‘curer of bacon, bacon-seller’.","2  English: perhaps also a variant of   Backler  ."]},{"name":"Batchelor","meanings":["English: status name for a young knight or novice at arms, Middle English and Old French <i>bacheler</i> (medieval Latin <i>baccalarius</i>). The word had already been extended to mean ‘(young) unmarried man’ by the 14th century, but it is unlikely that many bearers of the surname derive from the word in that sense.","History: The Reverend Stephen Bachiler (<i>c.</i> 1561–1656) was a Puritan nonconformist, born in Hampshire, England, who came to New England in 1632, at the age of 71. In 1638/9 he was the leader of the founders of Hampton, NH."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":19,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":28,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":39,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":55,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":57,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705210,"age":70,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":90,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"John Backler was born in 1530, in England. He had at least 1 son with Agnes Barber. He died in 1621, at the age of 91."},"et":{"1530–1621":"1530–1621","1531–Female":"1531–Surnud","1550–1584":"1550–1584","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1531":"1531","1530":"1530","1585":"1585","1584":"1584","1550":"1550","1549":"1549","England":"England","Dedham, Essex, England":"Dedham, Essex, England"},"fi":{"1530–1621":"1530–1621","1531–Female":"1531–Kuollut","1550–1584":"1550–1584","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1531":"1531","1530":"1530","1585":"1585","1584":"1584","1550":"1550","1549":"1549","England":"England","Dedham, Essex, England":"Dedham, Essex, England"},"fr":{"1530–1621":"1530–1621","1531–Female":"1531–Décédée","1550–1584":"1550–1584","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1531":"1531","1530":"1530","1585":"1585","1584":"1584","1550":"1550","1549":"1549","England":"Angleterre","Dedham, Essex, England":"Dedham, Essex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"John Backler est né en 1530, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Agnes Barber. Il est décédé en 1621,